[start section id="20112"]

#1 Resected recurrent adenocarcinoma of the rectum at the anastomosis; preoperatively, staged T3, N1, postoperative T3, N0
Prior to meeting with Mr. Epstein and his wife, I have had the opportunity to review his past medical records, laboratory tests, and imaging studies.  I have also had the opportunity to review this case in its entirety with my collaborating provider, Dr. Council, who is in agreement with this plan.  Discussed with Mr. Epstein typically would recommend adjuvant therapy in such a setting due to the fact that clinically he was considered to be a stage III rectal cancer.  Therefore, discussed with him various treatment options which include FOLFOX 6, oral Xeloda, or observation.  Mr. Epstein understands that the final decision is his.  He will be having a conversation with his local oncologist as to what is the next best step.  I informed him that there is no right or wrong answer.  Understands that it is a very personal decision.  Did inform him that if the cancer did reoccur that often times we can control cancer with chemotherapies.  However, once it does reoccur, the chances of curing an individual go down significantly.  He is going to take all of this under advisement.
#2 Follow-up
Mr. Epstein and his wife will be returning home to undergo additional therapy.  They will be contacting us with the name of the oncologist they would like all this information relayed to.  We will also then arrange for a CD copy of his most recent CT-scan to be sent to that facility.  He had several questions that I answered to his satisfaction.  He denies any further questions or concerns.  I did review with him the potential toxicities of the chemotherapy regimen which could include, but are not limited to, nausea, vomiting, decreased white count, infection, elevated temperature, constipation, diarrhea, cold sensitivity, and neuropathy.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: No, not interested in additional information.
PATIENT EDUCATION
Ready to learn, no apparent learning barriers were identified; learning preferences include listening.  Explained diagnosis and treatment plan; patient expressed understanding of the content.

[end section id="20112"]

