[start section id="20103"]

Me Epstein is a pleasant 70-year-old gentleman from Ong, NE 68452 Davey.  Seeing him today postoperatively to discuss recommendations regarding adjuvant therapy for a recurrent rectal adenocarcinoma at the anastomotic site.  For a comprehensive past medical history, please refer to my note dated September 20, 2010.  Briefly, his history is as follows:
1.  In 2007, diagnosed with prostate cancer.  Underwent resection and radiation therapy receiving  7380 cGy.  Initiated on Lupron.
2.  In 2009, diagnosed with bladder cancer, noninvasive, high-grade urothelial carcinoma.  Has had two scrapings performed.
3.  April 28, 2009, colonoscopy performed noting a mass at 30 cm, which was positive for villous adenoma with focal, high-grade dysplasia.  Additional lesion at 10-cm positive for invasive, grade 3 (of 4) adenocarcinoma.
4.  May 13, 2009, low-anterior resection performed elsewhere.  Pathology positive for invasive, grade 3 (of 4) adenocarcinoma.  Of three regional lymph nodes removed, all were negative for metastatic disease.  An additional adenoma with focal, high-grade dysplasia was present.  Surgical resected margins are negative (pT2, N0).
5.  July 6, 2010, colonoscopy noting ulceration at the region of the anastomosis.  Biopsies indeterminate.  Pathology reviewed  at Fond du Lac Health Center notes suspicious for invasive adenocarcinoma.
6.  July 20, 2010, proctoscopy noting a rectal mass which is biopsy positive for invasive, grade 3 (of 4) adenocarcinoma.  CT performed at-home negative for metastatic disease.
8.  August 3, 2010, presented to Fond du Lac Health Center for further workup.  Chest x-ray documenting nodular opacity at the left lung base laterally.  CT-scan noting a 9-mm nodule in the left lung base suspicious for metastasis.  Perirectal lymphadenopathy as well as indeterminate soft-tissue thickening and stranding in the perirectal space identified.  Several hepatic cysts as well as small hepatic lesions that are too small to characterize.
8.  August 4, 2010, PET scan noting uptake located at the anastomosis.  Low-grade uptake of perirectal lymph node.  Liver lesions were too small for PET analysis.
9.  August 9, 2010, EUS performed noting a mass at 6-cm that was ulcerated.  Peritumoral lymph node appear suspicious,  not biopsied due to location.
10. August 18, 2010, through September 10, 2010, completed chemoradiation therapy, receiving infusional 5-FU.
11.  September 21, 2010, Dr. Mckinney performed an APR with an omentoplasty as well as interoperative radiation therapy.  Pathology of the tissue from the APR positive for adenocarcinoma, moderately differentiated, with a foreign body giant-cell reaction.  The ulcer as well as tumor were present at the anastomotic site.  Of 14 retroperitoneal lymph nodes, all were negative for metastatic disease.  Surgical resected margins were negative.
Today, Mr. Epstein states that he is feeling extremely well.  Reports his appetite is improving.  Denies any nausea or vomiting.  Weight has been stable.  Energy level is also increasing.  States that he is trying to remain as active as possible.  Reports that ostomy appliance has been working well, absent of any blood or mucus.  He has had no complications with the appliance.  He denies chest pain, shortness-of-breath, lower-extremity edema, night sweats, or elevated temperature.

